AD  - Pontifical Catholic University, Paraná, Brazil
AB  - Recent findings showed that Digital Twin served multiple constituencies. However, the dilemma between scope and scale requires a sophisticated reference architecture, an appropriate set of technologies and an appropriate business model. Most studies in Digital Twin have focused only on manufacturing and proposed explicit structures and architecture, which have faced challenges in supporting different levels of integration through an agile process. Furthermore, no known empirical research has focused on exploring the relationships between the Digital Twin and mass individualization. Therefore, the main objective of this study was to identify suitable Industry 4.0 technologies and a holistic reference architecture model to realize the most challenging Digital Twin-enabled applications. In this study, a Digital Twin reference architecture was developed and applied in an industrial case. Furthermore, the Digital Twin as a Service (DTaaS) paradigm used for the digital transformation of unique wetlands with considerable advantages including smart scheduled maintenance, real-time monitoring, remote control and forecasting functionalities. The findings indicate that there is a significant relationship between the capabilities of Digital Twin as a Service and mass individualization. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.
