AD  - The Bartlett Faculty of the Built Environment, London, United Kingdom
AD  - Tsinghua University, Department of Construction Management, Beijing, China
AB  - The concept of Digital Twin (DT) has been greatly welcomed in Architectural, Engineering, Construction and Facility Management (AEC/FM) sector. From the concept to practice, the most dominant challenge could be the data management. Especially, the potentials of DTs in diverse application scenarios have been proposed from building to infrastructure, and to the city level under the requirements of multiple stakeholders. In this context, the data issues are aggravated facing the increasing heterogeneous data from the physical environment. However, there is limited research works examining and summarizing the data management issues when constructing DTs comprehensively in the AEC/FM sector. Therefore, this study aims to address this knowledge gap. First, a data environment with the enablers of data sources, data ecosystem, and data consumers connecting the physical and virtual spaces is defined. Specifically, the data ecosystem enabler is defined with five functional components (i.e., data collection and ingestion, data process and integration, data analysis and representation, data storage, and data pipelines). Then, 149 academic research works were selected as the data set for the systematic literature review. The review and analysis are conducted based on the structure of the enablers in a data environment. This research intends to bring thorough and practical insights of DTs from building to city level assets for researchers, practitioners, and policy makers. © 2024 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.
